{"success": true, "message": "Fetched question.", "data": {"showTimer": true, "showAttemptInsight": true, "playSounds": true, "dontShowCorrectAnswerImmediately": false, "_id": "66bcbd88ae81d148616b1211", "type": "singleCorrect", "level": 1, "category": null, "approximateTimeRequired": 45, "imageBaseUrl": null, "helperText": null, "source": "MOG", "classes": [], "exams": ["615d76e4c52ffa3c944600e1"], "subjects": ["615d70bd9948bc1b21da2b1f"], "chapters": ["615d6fed2b295b085ab6ebab"], "topics": [], "concepts": [], "microConcepts": [], "questionLabels": [], "previousYearPapers": [{"_id": "64b850012a7d64ecd80b00a1", "title": "NEET 2002", "isVisible": true}], "question": {"text": "In a hydrogen atom, the energy of the first excited state is $-3.4 \\mathrm{eV}$. Then, find out the K.E. of the same orbit of the hydrogen atom.", "image": null}, "options": [{"id": "3GSUj", "text": "$+3.4 \\mathrm{eV}$", "image": null, "isCorrect": true}, {"id": "Q8tKF", "text": "$+6.8 \\mathrm{eV}$", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "vwhc9", "text": "$-13.6 \\mathrm{eV}$", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "0CwiP", "text": "$+13.6 \\mathrm{eV}$", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}], "correctValue": null, "solution": {"text": "For hydrogen atom,\nThe kinetic energy is equal to the negative of the total energy. And the potential energy is equal to the twice of the total energy.\nThe first excited state energy of orbital $=-3.4 \\mathrm{eV}$ and the kinetic energy of same orbital $=-(-3.4 \\mathrm{eV})$ $=3.4 \\mathrm{eV}$\nRelated Theory\nIn search of its lowest energy configuration the Hydrogen atom in the first excited state will de-excite to the ground-state, by emitting a photon of energy $\\left(E_2-E_\\nu\\right)$.\nCaution\nThe energy in an excited state is nothing but kinetic energy.", "image": null}, "videoSolution": null, "masterId": "MOGNEPYQ68971821", "numericalLowerLimit": null, "numericalUpperLimit": null, "bucket": "", "isRemoved": false, "cpyqbSubjects": ["615